org.eclipse.dataset

Class AbstractDataset

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.eclipse.dataset.LazyDatasetBase
      • org.eclipse.dataset.AbstractDataset
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, Dataset, IDataset, IErrorDataset, ILazyDataset, IMetadataProvider, INameable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AbstractCompoundDataset, BooleanDatasetBase, ByteDataset, DoubleDataset, FloatDataset, IntegerDataset, LongDataset, ObjectDatasetBase, ShortDataset, StringDatasetBase

    public abstract class AbstractDataset
extends LazyDatasetBase
implements Dataset
    Generic container class for data

    Each subclass has an array of primitive types, elements of this array are grouped or compounded to make items

    Data items can be boolean, integer, float, complex float, vector float, etc

    See Also:
    Serialized Form

      • getTransposedView

        public Dataset getTransposedView(int... axes)
        Description copied from interface: ILazyDataset
        Permute copy of dataset's axes so that given order is old order: 
          axisPerm = (p(0), p(1),...) => newdata(n(0), n(1),...) = olddata(o(0), o(1), ...)
  such that n(i) = o(p(i)) for all i
        I.e. for a 3D dataset (1,0,2) implies the new dataset has its 1st dimension running along the old dataset's 2nd dimension and the new 2nd is the old 1st. The 3rd dimension is left unchanged.
        Specified by:
        getTransposedView in interface Dataset
        Specified by:
        getTransposedView in interface ILazyDataset
        Parameters:
        axes - if zero length then axes order reversed
        Returns:
        remapped view of data

      • variance

        public java.lang.Number variance(boolean isDatasetWholePopulation)
        Description copied from interface: Dataset
        The sample variance can be calculated in two ways: if the dataset is considered as the entire population then the sample variance is simply the second central moment: 
            sum((x_i - m)^2)/N
 where {x_i} are set of N population values and m is the mean
    m = sum(x_i)/N
        Otherwise, if the dataset is a set of samples (with replacement) from the population then 
            sum((x_i - m)^2)/(N-1)
 where {x_i} are set of N sample values and m is the unbiased estimate of the mean
    m = sum(x_i)/N
        Note that the second definition is also the unbiased estimator of population variance.
        Specified by:
        variance in interface Dataset
        Returns:
        sample variance

      • variance

        public Dataset variance(int axis)
        Specified by:
